91-4fd6-99e3-67c8d9c1ad5f\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"inquiry\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡོངས་སུ་ཚོལ་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"paryeṣaṇā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"yongs su tshol ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b8a50087-18c2-468e-a3a0-0e23baf58acd\",\"authority\":\"1d2816b9-3066-48b4-a1a3-8fa6080f6fa9\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAn important form of Buddhist meditation focusing on developing insight into the nature of phenomena. Often presented as part of a pair of meditation techniques, the other being śamatha, “calm abiding”.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"insight\",\"tibetan\":\"ལྷག་མཐོང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vipaśyanā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lhag mthong\"}},{\"uuid\":\"3a4a1b1d-ab93-48ef-ac30-e3d27aa50ad5\",\"authority\":\"8f934870-689e-44f4-a9b4-089350e47d2c\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"intelligence\",\"tibetan\":\"བློ་གྲོས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mati\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"blo gros\"}},{\"uuid\":\"1d91dcb1-52df-4912-8c74-aded9c238d9e\",\"authority\":\"99a52c06-2268-45ba-9749-93d1043a002a\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"intention\",\"tibetan\":\"བསམ་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"āśaya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bsam pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ca8d8df3-7de2-4775-971e-dbd3778e963b\",\"authority\":\"463df96d-7bdc-47ab-b3ec-5f96a9a7d3f5\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eIn our text, the specific \u003cspan\u003equality\u003c/span\u003e of \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003evicāra\u003c/em\u003e is to remain mindful of \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003e\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-049-001-1577\\\"\u003enimitta\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/em\u003e in the sense of “mentally watching” or noting them without engaging in a more discursive way.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"investigation\",\"tibetan\":\"དཔྱོད་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vicāra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dpyod pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a8d6df7c-812d-4423-b3a2-34b5066aaa20\",\"authority\":\"a7b369fe-fecb-43b8-9447-c5373ac1fcf7\",\"definition\":\"$6b\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Jambudvīpa\",\"tibetan\":\"འཛམ་བུ་གླིང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"jambudvīpa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’dzam bu gling\"}},{\"uuid\":\"3594f47d-ff91-4b21-bd7c-82d556493a8b\",\"authority\":\"b05711ee-d07d-4411-a35c-b38a9b5d7bad\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"joy\",\"tibetan\":\"དགའ་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"prīti\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dga’ ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b0ac2880-07b9-42f3-b9af-99161d3032ab\",\"authority\":\"3ba55b85-25b2-43a5-946b-328e1b7de765\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eType of Sanskrit compound.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"karmadhāraya\",\"tibetan\":\"\",\"sanskrit\":\"karmadhāraya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a4455dd9-22db-4f29-a5e3-076d724fb689\",\"authority\":\"eb9808a0-e1f1-4af3-b542-eae3409ce56b\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e(cf. Sanskrit text in Matsuda 2013, p. 940 \u003cem class=\\\"distinct\\\"\u003ead\u003c/em\u003e Lamotte VIII.41). \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eDhāraya\u003c/em\u003e is a causative imperative of \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003edhṛ\u003c/em\u003e-.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"keep in mind, keep it in mind\",\"tibetan\":\"ཟུང་ཤིག\",\"sanskrit\":\"dhāraya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"zung shig\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ce6a97b5-8b0b-4542-b216-c7710d4abef3\",\"authority\":\"2ab5a89b-4a04-4b78-940a-4de89d4f909e\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"keep it in mind\",\"tibetan\":\"གཟུང་བར་བགྱི།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dhārayāmi\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gzung bar bgyi\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b63e4eab-dd3f-456e-9620-cc0bdf87a46b\",\"authority\":\"b57a5182-b1eb-4168-bd5f-28ca6def5a9f\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eA class of nonhuman beings that resemble humans to the degree that their very name‍—which means “is that human?”‍—suggests some confusion as to their divine status. Kinnaras are mythological beings found in both Buddhist and Brahmanical literature, where they are portrayed as creatures half human, half animal. They are often depicted as highly skilled celestial musicians.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"kinnara\",\"tibetan\":\"\",\"sanskrit\":\"kinnara\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c287428b-3da2-4882-bc75-75478558cd8c\",\"authority\":\"d8cb7442-265c-4865-b071-ce14ee9b7af3\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eWorld of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-049-001-1726\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-049-001-1708\\\"\u003eViśālakīrti\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Kīrtimat\",\"tibetan\":\"གྲགས་པ་ཅན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kīrtimat\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"grags pa can\"}},{\"uuid\":\"6f25d16d-1853-4fba-b9ff-0d723f26f1f1\",\"authority\":\"2f0b9870-c0cb-4be6-baaf-5a9e0bc8765b\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eMahāvyutpatti 6558. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"label\",\"tibetan\":\"བཏགས་པའི་ཚིག, མིང་དུ་བཏགས།, འཇིག་རྟེན་གྱི་ཐ་སྙད་དུ་བཏགས་པ།, འཇིག་རྟེན་གྱི་ཐ་སྙད་དུ་བཏགས་པའམ་འཇིག་རྟེན་གྱི་ཐ་སྙད།, འཇིག་རྟེན་གྱི་ཐ་སྙད་དུ་བཏགས་པའམ་འཇིག་རྟེན་ཐ་སྙད།, འཇིག་རྟེན་གྱི་ཐ་སྙད།, འཇིག་རྟེན་གྱི་མིང་དུ་བཏགས་པ།, འཇིག་རྟེན་ཐ་སྙད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"lokasaṃjñā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"btags pa’i tshig, ming du btags, ’jig rten gyi ming du btags pa, ’jig rten gyi tha snyad, ’jig rten gyi tha snyad du btags pa, ’jig rten gyi tha snyad du btags pa’am ’jig rten gyi tha snyad, ’jig rten gyi tha snyad du btags pa’am ’jig rten tha snyad, ’jig rten tha snyad\"}},{\"uuid\":\"94d0017e-8be3-4270-af1b-14bb9860d351\",\"authority\":\"83590e2d-4630-4c79-82d9-5f6af9eeaf58\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"lacked certainty\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡིད་གཉིས་ཅན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vimati\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"yid gnyis can\"}},{\"uuid\":\"97914f80-f503-4438-8c21-1d5b0ee1a039\",\"authority\":\"d5b6340d-920f-4ac8-b731-9e6dfc0aa682\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAlso translated here as “\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-049-001-1585\\\"\u003epredisposition\u003c/span\u003e.”\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"latent disposition, predisposed, predisposition\",\"tibetan\":\"བག་ལ་ཉལ།, བག་ལ་ཉལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"anuśaya, anuśaya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bag la nyal, bag la nyal\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f1499914-213c-45c2-af13-3a1bbd1d7884\",\"authority\":\"d5b6340d-920f-4ac8-b731-9e6dfc0aa682\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAlso translated here are “\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-049-001-1524\\\"\u003elatent disposition\u003c/span\u003e.”\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"latent disposition, predisposed, predisposition\",\"tibetan\":\"བག་ལ་ཉལ།, བག་ལ་ཉལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"anuśaya, anuśaya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bag la nyal, bag la nyal\"}},{\"uuid\":\"329707c5-9855-4bfd-8094-023a57e9c0cc\",\"authority\":\"323ce00e-0e38-4c57-8f71-8500e60e1072\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eSee Hayal 1978: 229.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"liberation\",\"tibetan\":\"རྣམ་པར་ཐར་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vimokṣa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rnam par thar pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"dbd40a43-df25-4e46-89d2-eab8871be13e\",\"authority\":\"4f975a59-f013-411f-b02e-6f672fc00fdd\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"lies hidden\",\"tibetan\":\"རབ་ཏུ་སྦྱོར་བར་བྱེད་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"pralayanata\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rab tu sbyor bar byed pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0f1ee18a-69c6-4a15-b2ea-849e6fa47f40\",\"authority\":\"54db9911-43cb-47bb-b615-2e0797162a5f\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"literal\",\"tibetan\":\"སྒྲ་ཇི་བཞིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"yathāruta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sgra ji bzhin\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2ce48dfb-9147-4d14-9059-2860bd12bbb6\",\"authority\":\"3f0c6991-d3cb-45ca-81b1-ec276e3b59c8\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"magic illusion\",\"tibetan\":\"སྒྱུ་མ་བྱས་པ།, སྒྱུ་མའི་ལས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sgyu ma byas pa, sgyu ma’i las\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c54a5e3f-48fb-4f8b-962d-7af79365eda5\",\"authority\":\"eb1c6fc0-d2f8-4d3e-8fad-825f71769dd7\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eLiterally “great serpents,” mahoragas are supernatural beings depicted as large, subterranean beings with human torsos and heads and the lower bodies of serpents. Their movements are said to cause earthquakes, and they make up a class of subterranean geomantic spirits whose movement through the seasons and months of the year is deemed significant for construction projects.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"mahoraga\",\"tibetan\":\"\",\"sanskrit\":\"mahoraga\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"\"}},{\"uuid\":\"91e6a61d-94e5-4e5e-9d70-0c9f940e123e\",\"authority\":\"cdfb8e4f-6d68-4c38-a3c5-5bd8897f3897\",\"definition\":\"$6c\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Maitreya\",\"tibetan\":\"བྱམས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"maitreya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"byams pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d104e5f6-70ef-4e6c-91eb-3174a2dcb1a0\",\"authority\":\"a406d2ef-b447-47ad-b1c2-4d216fb8492e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eRegarding the term “\u003cspan class=\\\"ignore\\\"\u003ethought\u003c/span\u003e” as a translation for the Sanskrit \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003emanas\u003c/em\u003e, see Schmithausen 2014.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"manas, thought\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡིད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"manas\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"yid\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2a98d56d-966b-4979-88d4-07faedd5ab1d\",\"authority\":\"0aace3c4-3c66-4dfe-aa85-ddb2fb6408e0\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe name of a bodhisattva \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-049-001-1624\\\"\u003estage\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Manifest\",\"tibetan\":\"མངོན་དུ་གྱུར་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"abhimukhī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mngon du gyur pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c300e42c-ad29-483f-90dc-e12c40c88f75\",\"authority\":\"320c5523-4cde-4365-aeb1-3e69be9b0e42\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eMañjuśrī is one of the “eight close sons of the Buddha” and a bodhisattva who embodies wisdom. He is a major figure in the Mahāyāna sūtras, appearing often as an interlocutor of the Buddha. In his most well-known iconographic form, he is portrayed bearing the sword of wisdom in his right hand and a volume of the \u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003ePrajñā­pāramitā­sūtra\u003c/cite\u003e in his left. To his name, Mañjuśrī, meaning “Gentle and Glorious One,” is often added the epithet Kumārabhūta, “having a youthful form.” He is also called Mañjughoṣa, Mañjusvara, and Pañcaśikha.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Mañjuśrī\",\"tibetan\":\"འཇམ་དཔལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mañjuśrī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’jam dpal\"}},{\"uuid\":\"48821336-fbe5-48e9-81e7-6f76aa69a176\",\"authority\":\"d968cac3-fbb6-493e-9957-c8ce0201fc9c\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAn early name for the Abhidharmapiṭaka and also a germinal list or index of topics.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"mātṛkā\",\"tibetan\":\"མ་མོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mātṛkā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ma mo\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0854b4b8-badd-407c-b42a-fa1e4a29622e\",\"authority\":\"dc830f27-bd72-456a-8914-ad8e4a4ae428\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"meaning of true reality\",\"tibetan\":\"དེ་ཁོ་ནའི་དོན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"tattvārtha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"de kho na’i don\"}},{\"uuid\":\"64909594-634f-47a9-a00e-6fa88f9f4b39\",\"authority\":\"72b9bc1c-896f-4242-998d-15fd6a7a4b90\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eSee Hayal 1978, p. 221.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"meditative absorption\",\"tibetan\":\"བསམ་གཏན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dhyāna\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bsam gtan\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c6a99478-21ea-4433-8f6f-40ddab891514\",\"authority\":\"baedd459-5b40-4a1c-af5c-ff828b4929ea\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"mental appearance\",\"tibetan\":\"སེམས་ཀྱི་མཚན་མ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"cittanimitta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sems kyi mtshan ma\"}},{\"uuid\":\"492fa82e-903f-4538-8003-a78d0313a557\",\"authority\":\"466f219e-3bb6-4a85-a1d5-0e722ab70b94\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"mental elaboration\",\"tibetan\":\"སྤྲོས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"prapañca\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"spros pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d6851c20-665e-4ad5-b43b-a2b51dca335f\",\"authority\":\"48de3e6b-b841-4e34-a0e5-a360bf30f7d1\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"mental imprint\",\"tibetan\":\"བག་ཆགས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vāsanā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bag chags\"}},{\"uuid\":\"60bbf8d8-91e4-4413-8a02-edbdb0ad89b0\",\"authority\":\"5136be49-c4b6-4096-a119-359fd10989c5\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"mental inspection, pratisaṃkhyā\",\"tibetan\":\"སོ་སོར་བརྟག་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"pratisaṃkhyā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"so sor brtag pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7a87b289-e6ba-4c97-bb9e-1d3868d217f2\",\"authority\":\"b3d561fa-6d30-48bb-83b0-feebc53dc285\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"mental state\",\"tibetan\":\"སེམས་ལས་བྱུང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"caitasika\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sems las byung ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f081ad45-1d8a-4264-8b75-5ad325e8c7f8\",\"authority\":\"f2cbdf52-fb59-48b9-ab78-dba315b9aed3\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"mental stillness\",\"tibetan\":\"ཞི་གནས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śamatha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"zhi gnas\"}},{\"uuid\":\"8fe6483c-7a2f-4114-886e-1185bf09c76d\",\"authority\":\"291d39a8-4841-48f9-86ff-2f4f5d3aaf7e\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"mere representation, merely a representation, vijñaptimātra\",\"tibetan\":\"རྣམ་པར་རིག་པ་ཙམ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vijñaptimātra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rnam par rig pa tsam\"}},{\"uuid\":\"74cc489e-8206-4d93-8748-ca72b2ec0f85\",\"authority\":\"85f71dae-44c6-4a92-b114-b0151bf47f19\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eSchmithausen translates this term with “all-seed \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-049-001-1542\\\"\u003emind\u003c/span\u003e,” which can mean both “\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-049-001-1542\\\"\u003emind\u003c/span\u003e \u003cspan class=\\\"ignore\\\"\u003econtaining all the seeds\u003c/span\u003e” or “\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-049-001-1542\\\"\u003emind\u003c/span\u003e consisting of all the seeds.” See Schmithausen 2014, p. 65, n. 221.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"mind containing all the seeds\",\"tibetan\":\"ས་བོན་ཐམས་ཅད་པའི་སེམས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sarvabījaṃ cittam\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sa bon thams cad pa’i sems\"}},{\"uuid\":\"65792e60-aad1-40ff-9557-4769d0a35662\",\"authority\":\"48ce895d-9b42-44b8-bf4a-a21d542a0e92\",\"definition\":\"$6d\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"mindfulness\",\"tibetan\":\"དྲན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"smṛti\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dran pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2468b23c-6789-4da5-aa73-40a87a8fdf00\",\"authority\":\"bbc77e13-4bdd-4909-bfdd-d8a299ca4508\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eA class of nonhuman beings who live in subterranean aquatic environments, where they guard wealth and sometimes also teachings. Nāgas are associated with serpents and have a snakelike appearance. In Buddhist art and in written accounts, they are regularly portrayed as half human and half snake, and they are also said to have the ability to change into human form. Some nāgas are Dharma protectors, but they can also bring retribution if they are disturbed. They may likewise fight one another, wage war, and destroy the lands of others by causing lightning, hail, and flooding.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"nāga\",\"tibetan\":\"ཀླུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"nāga\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"klu\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5013e6d2-12f8-4bcc-ad0b-57d8d2ad1c5b\",\"authority\":\"9e221007-a3ae-4f9e-92ef-a128242d15b4\",\"definition\":\"$6e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"naturally present\",\"tibetan\":\"རང་བཞིན་དུ་གནས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"nisargabhāva, svabhāvasthita, svabhāvasthita\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rang bzhin du gnas pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"9b620497-2ccc-4aa5-b0d4-b22530a83cd0\",\"authority\":\"ef7d95cf-c872-4e13-aa85-0676d1c13cd2\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"nature of things\",\"tibetan\":\"ཇི་ལྟ་བ་བཞིན་དུ་ཡོད་པ་ཉིད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"yathāvadbhāvikatā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ji lta ba bzhin du yod pa nyid\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7696ecf2-46e6-4c50-81e8-de20c2de8f9e\",\"authority\":\"72fe25a7-c632-4b20-845a-5ff2b0a39631\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"negate, negated, negation\",\"tibetan\":\"སྐུར་པ་འདེབས་པ།, སྐུར་པ་འདེབས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"apavāda, apavāda\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"skur pa ’debs, skur pa ’debs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"637a0d08-6c42-4c32-a448-a854aca7bbc4\",\"authority\":\"72fe25a7-c632-4b20-845a-5ff2b0a39631\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"negate, negated, negation\",\"tibetan\":\"སྐུར་པ་འདེབས་པ།, སྐུར་པ་འདེབས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"apavāda, apavāda\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"skur pa ’debs, skur pa ’debs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"fd5e7a88-cfd1-4d07-a123-7c1171eb59de\",\"authority\":\"0a5ff6a2-7316-4d27-a146-2744cac1380d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eLit. “the world beyond [death].”\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"next life\",\"tibetan\":\"འཇིག་རྟེན་ཕ་རོལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"paraloka\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’jig rten pha rol\"}},{\"uuid\":\"72f80123-e9e7-421f-a43f-59ce107c9879\",\"authority\":\"d53afc9b-bc4e-4c35-907b-aa41b5973b82\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eIntroductory part of a sūtra . \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"nidāna\",\"tibetan\":\"གླེང་གཞི།\",\"sanskrit\":\"nidāna\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gleng gzhi\"}},{\"uuid\":\"47d7ce80-c6de-4173-bf62-5997019ee7de\",\"authority\":\"5fffaf6c-b938-4182-b91d-57a90be7be61\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"nimitta, phenomenal appearance\",\"tibetan\":\"མཚན་མ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"nimitta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mtshan ma\"}},{\"uuid\":\"957da5d5-795e-4533-909b-58063c94b409\",\"authority\":\"4a9c787d-e93e-4757-b5c4-65281f956020\",\"definition\":\"$6f\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"nirvāṇa\",\"tibetan\":\"མྱ་ངན་ལས་འདས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"nirvāṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mya ngan las ’das pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"bfa6b55c-3da0-4cca-9355-a5dae8884e1d\",\"authority\":\"207f5f53-fc1e-434b-8151-bc7b63581fd5\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe Sanskrit \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eārya\u003c/em\u003e has the general meaning of a noble person, one of a higher class or caste. In Buddhist literature, depending on the context, it often means specifically one who has gained the realization of the path and is superior for that reason. In particular, it applies to stream enterers, once-returners, non-returners, and worthy ones (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003earhats\u003c/em\u003e) and is also used as an epithet of bodhisattvas. In the five-path system, it refers to someone who has achieved at least the path of seeing (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003edarśanamārga\u003c/em\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"noble being\",\"tibetan\":\"འཕགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ārya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’phags pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f72c6722-81a1-48c8-9569-2e4976845d31\",\"authority\":\"e5604cfb-e911-4e7f-9708-377807a2a901\",\"definition\":\"$70\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"non-Buddhist\",\"tibetan\":\"མུ་སྟེགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"tīrthika\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mu stegs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"8add1668-c7f5-4eae-ad45-edb7c22be603\",\"authority\":\"85e00c7b-2c93-4630-9874-f0735613a307\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eMahāvyutpatti 1717. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"nondual, nonduality\",\"tibetan\":\"གཉིས་སུ་མེད་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"advaya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gnyis su med pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d84afd2b-0e37-47ca-b1a1-00c09c47e855\",\"authority\":\"7f44b253-417f-4776-a6e4-b6cc7b00b529\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eSee Schmithausen 2014, p. 362, §306.5 and n. 1644.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"object conducive to purification, viśuddhyālambana\",\"tibetan\":\"རྣམ་པར་དག་པའི་དམིགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"viśuddhyālambana\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rnam par dag pa’i dmigs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a5b75fc2-e4c9-4db3-a72b-3763d9f67e14\",\"authority\":\"557eae60-59b1-4995-b025-02d8d854f402\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAlso translated here as “\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-049-001-1622\\\"\u003esphere of activity\u003c/span\u003e.” See \u003ca href=\\\"end-notes.xhtml#UT22084-049-001-181\\\" data-pointer-type=\\\"id\\\"\u003en.42\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"object of experience, objects of experience, sphere of activity\",\"tibetan\":\"སྤྱོད་ཡུལ།, སྤྱོད་ཡུལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"gocara, gocara\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"spyod yul, spyod yul\"}},{\"uuid\":\"bc95597e-a51a-4c98-9df7-496f7ffe1837\",\"authority\":\"557eae60-59b1-4995-b025-02d8d854f402\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAlso translated here as “\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-049-001-1559\\\"\u003eobject of experience\u003c/span\u003e.”\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"object of experience, objects of experience, sphere of activity\",\"tibetan\":\"སྤྱོད་ཡུལ།, སྤྱོད་ཡུལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"gocara, gocara\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"spyod yul, spyod yul\"}},{\"uuid\":\"cf9988ae-d23d-4a8e-a24a-2f5503ee7f00\",\"authority\":\"c84d1179-092a-471a-9fad-f1dbc03b5917\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"object, thing, vastu\",\"tibetan\":\"ངོ་བོ།, དངོས་པོ།, དངོས་པོ།, ཡུལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bhāva, vastu\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dngos po, dngos po, ngo bo, yul\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c5f03657-2f4a-4be8-89cc-ab14d505c429\",\"authority\":\"c84d1179-092a-471a-9fad-f1dbc03b5917\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAlso translated here as “\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-049-001-1557\\\"\u003eobject\u003c/span\u003e.”\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"object, thing, vastu\",\"tibetan\":\"ངོ་བོ།, དངོས་པོ།, དངོས་པོ།, ཡུལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bhāva, vastu\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dngos po, dngos po, ngo bo, yul\"}},{\"uuid\":\"4e20b9bb-fecd-416d-8d29-c61c63ee020d\",\"authority\":\"8fd2314c-8a07-4bad-8f2b-f059e94fb1b5\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"obscuration of cognitive objects\",\"tibetan\":\"ཤེས་བྱའི་སྒྲིབ་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"jñeyāvaraṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"shes bya’i sgrib pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ef7846b8-a33d-4ddc-9b8f-762f74c19b97\",\"authority\":\"86d8b479-20e3-4327-8c21-601f9950abde\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"obstacle\",\"tibetan\":\"གེགས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vibandha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gegs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a9865148-8f12-4e17-81e7-ebadc56c7fac\",\"authority\":\"62a6f736-b058-4bf8-b8cb-549ec7850de0\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe obscurations to liberation and omniscience. They are generally categorized as two types: affective obscurations (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003ekleśāvaraṇa\u003c/em\u003e), the arising of afflictive emotions; and cognitive obscurations (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003ejñeyāvaraṇa\u003c/em\u003e), those caused by misapprehension and incorrect understanding about the nature of reality. \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe term is used also as a reference to a set five hindrances on the path: longing for sense pleasures (Skt. \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003ekāmacchanda\u003c/em\u003e), malice (Skt. \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003evyāpāda\u003c/em\u003e), sloth and torpor (Skt. \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003estyānamiddha\u003c/em\u003e), excitement and remorse (Skt. \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eauddhatyakaukṛtya\u003c/em\u003e), and doubt (Skt. \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003evicikitsā\u003c/em\u003e). \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"obstruction\",\"tibetan\":\"སྒྲིབ་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"āvaraṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sgrib pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"cbea69eb-013b-4e05-aff4-98b5c2b872ef\",\"authority\":\"7b15ba33-9719-4a6a-8213-60f8eda01bdc\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"of a single character, of a single nature\",\"tibetan\":\"རོ་གཅིག་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ekarasa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ro gcig pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c6e53e48-0536-4ad4-b587-c755bc2bf569\",\"authority\":\"664bf30a-2bb6-48d4-ad62-b4dde324c554\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"one-pointedness of mind\",\"tibetan\":\"སེམས་རྩེ་གཅིག་པ་ཉིད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"cittaikāgratā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sems rtse gcig pa nyid\"}},{\"uuid\":\"50e629b7-b87f-4638-a601-6473a169ebed\",\"authority\":\"06c5e280-6677-4307-8935-fbd23872a713\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"ordinary being\",\"tibetan\":\"སོ་སོའི་སྐྱེ་བོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"pṛthag­jana\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"so so’i skye bo\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f0218001-adfb-405e-8ff8-5bb6e9bb4d14\",\"authority\":\"d65d6d8a-b8ea-4316-9950-39a567303f02\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"other-dependent defining characteristic\",\"tibetan\":\"གཞན་གྱི་དབང་གི་མཚན་ཉིད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"para­tantra­lakṣaṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gzhan gyi dbang gi mtshan nyid\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c475e47d-cad4-48bb-b82e-fc4f919a67c2\",\"authority\":\"5d4bc623-32db-41b1-8b96-ff9544329ece\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"other-dependent, other-dependent essence, paratantra\",\"tibetan\":\"གཞན་གྱི་དབང་།, གཞན་གྱི་དབང་གི་ངོ་བོ་ཉིད།, གཞན་གྱི་དབང་གི་རང་བཞིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"paratantra, paratantrasvabhāva\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gzhan gyi dbang, gzhan gyi dbang gi ngo bo nyid, gzhan gyi dbang gi rang bzhin\"}},{\"uuid\":\"fb9fb5d2-8aff-4d2a-9d7d-daf23f8e320c\",\"authority\":\"5d4bc623-32db-41b1-8b96-ff9544329ece\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"other-dependent, other-dependent essence, paratantra\",\"tibetan\":\"གཞན་གྱི་དབང་།, གཞན་གྱི་དབང་གི་ངོ་བོ་ཉིད།, གཞན་གྱི་དབང་གི་རང་བཞིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"paratantra, paratantrasvabhāva\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gzhan gyi dbang, gzhan gyi dbang gi ngo bo nyid, gzhan gyi dbang gi rang bzhin\"}},{\"uuid\":\"537e957c-58b2-4ce7-88cc-ad811243d1ba\",\"authority\":\"50c784ae-1581-46dc-8847-828dd548a541\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bodhisattva mahāsattva.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Para­mārtha­samud­gata\",\"tibetan\":\"དོན་དམ་ཡང་དག་འཕགས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"para­mārtha­samud­gata\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"don dam yang dag ’phags\"}},{\"uuid\":\"33143ccb-3a56-409f-8f58-2dcca1a4ec97\",\"authority\":\"be11b8dd-4778-46e8-ae9d-69f060ba11a8\",\"definition\":\"$71\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"parinirvāṇa\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡོངས་སུ་མྱ་ངན་ལས་འདས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"parinirvāṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"yongs su mya ngan las ’das pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"1125cb3f-8f1d-46e1-bfb5-a2b3f111d597\",\"authority\":\"64a50fd8-0fd0-4a50-a5f8-c081ba5ef861\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA term meaning acceptance, forbearance, or patience. As the third of the six perfections, patience is classified into three kinds: the capacity to tolerate abuse from sentient beings, to tolerate the hardships of the path to buddhahood, and to tolerate the profound nature of reality. As a term referring to a bodhisattva’s realization, \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003edharmakṣānti\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003echos la bzod pa\u003c/em\u003e) can refer to the ways one becomes “receptive” to the nature of Dharma, and it can be an abbreviation of \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eanutpattikadharmakṣānti\u003c/em\u003e, “forbearance for the unborn nature, or nonproduction, of dharmas.”\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"patience\",\"tibetan\":\"བཟོད་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bzod pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"8423d12c-563e-4560-8beb-62f5bc2a0e0e\",\"authority\":\"17efa17c-af36-4e80-bd71-0ddcb9a5d4b2\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"paying attention\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡང་དག་པར་རྗེས་སུ་མཐོང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"samanupaśyati\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"yang dag par rjes su mthong ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"26a8496f-e0c7-4eb4-a5d0-7e54ec4907f5\",\"authority\":\"390484ac-3b55-4fbe-8956-05a7625e2823\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"perfection\",\"tibetan\":\"ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"pāramitā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"pha rol tu phyin pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"24e7603e-5519-44d8-9ade-f9de3277c82d\",\"authority\":\"d8acec8f-b4a6-474e-9ce4-27ffb7a009cf\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe sixth of the six perfections, it refers to the profound understanding of the emptiness of all phenomena, the realization of ultimate reality. It is often personified as a female deity, worshiped as the “Mother of All Buddhas” (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003esarva­jina­mātā\u003c/em\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"perfection of wisdom\",\"tibetan\":\"ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"prajñāpāramitā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"shes rab kyi pha rol tu phyin pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7d937a90-aa59-4202-ac1d-ae67ce02564e\",\"authority\":\"037a0b7e-1f77-41da-8f6a-24f6ed496dd3\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eMahāvyutpatti 351. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"perfectly pure cognition\",\"tibetan\":\"བློ་ཤིན་ཏུ་རྣམ་པར་དག་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"suviśuddhabuddhiḥ\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"blo shin tu rnam par dag pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"3f200917-a25b-4eb3-ae79-00e2983a2a3e\",\"authority\":\"f25d4b26-db3b-4e43-acf5-8a276f2c6ece\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eMahāvyutpatti 360. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"perfectly skilled in the sameness of the three times\",\"tibetan\":\"དུས་གསུམ་མཉམ་པ་ཉིད་ཚར་ཕྱིན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"tryadhvasamatāniryātaḥ\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dus gsum mnyam pa nyid tshar phyin pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"73574cde-38df-4f75-ac34-711b2bb284ed\",\"authority\":\"abf70e90-d595-4f7b-b05e-3b3e00f97212\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"phenomenal appearance of conditioned phenomena, saṃskāranimitta\",\"tibetan\":\"\",\"sanskrit\":\"saṃskāranimitta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d292f887-b99c-44d5-a301-5feccdbfea18\",\"authority\":\"39ed7fa9-8dd5-4d24-b72b-51b7699c7b11\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"point where phenomena end\",\"tibetan\":\"དངོས་པོའི་མཐའ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vastvanta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dngos po’i mtha’\"}},{\"uuid\":\"88c055af-6986-493b-8e94-603f99e21461\",\"authority\":\"523994e8-46d1-49e1-b11e-ae9c32444df4\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"point where the sphere of space ends\",\"tibetan\":\"ནམ་མཁའི་ཁམས་ཀྱི་མཐས་གཏུགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ākāśadhātuparyavasānaḥ\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nam mkha’i khams kyi mthas gtugs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"04a9d1c7-3855-42ed-a2ea-197b8d6961b3\",\"authority\":\"cc15c527-3983-42b9-952c-130307ed21dd\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eMahāvyutpatti 366. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"possessed the gnosis bodhisattvas vow to accomplish\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡེ་ཤེས་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཐམས་ཅད་ཀྱིས་ཡང་དག་པར་མནོས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sarvabodhisattvasampratīcchītajñanaḥ\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ye shes byang chub sems dpa’ thams cad kyis yang dag par mnos pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"9024eb1a-894f-474a-a2f8-092004f5819a\",\"authority\":\"f9915f1a-87d8-459b-8cfb-a0c34ddb118a\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eTechnical term in Buddhist logic.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"pra­siddhānu­māṇa\",\"tibetan\":\"\",\"sanskrit\":\"pra­siddhānu­māṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b59f2d19-c522-4451-888f-667b65eb7a17\",\"authority\":\"8d55a3e8-7b85-4be6-9302-c2e9e1730166\",\"definition\":\"$72\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"prātimokṣa\",\"tibetan\":\"སོ་སོར་ཐར་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"prātimokṣa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"so sor thar pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"1e90dc88-d44c-4d41-a2d6-f27e9685ce7f\",\"authority\":\"ab5ca5c6-a7f2-4847-bdd5-9ae84c22be14\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"primordially in the state of peace\",\"tibetan\":\"གཟོད་མ་ནས་ཞིབ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ādiśānta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gzod ma nas zhib\"}},{\"uuid\":\"decacab0-e95b-4b92-a188-67f324db0df0\",\"authority\":\"f301ad97-0383-4132-8fa9-e4d39efa353b\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"prince\",\"tibetan\":\"གཞོན་ནུར་གྱུར་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kumārabhūta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gzhon nur gyur pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5bbdff37-d41c-459d-ad7c-4998c585959c\",\"authority\":\"02ab32cf-20d1-4280-827a-f966a932539c\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"principle of reason based on cause and effect, principle of reason based on cause and effect\",\"tibetan\":\"བྱ་བ་བྱེད་པའི་རིགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kārya­kāraṇayukti\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bya ba byed pa’i rigs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2188d8a6-2c50-4ba4-b26d-12ace6361e34\",\"authority\":\"92af4dbc-f835-4f9d-84ac-f45458da4db9\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"principle of reason based on dependence, principle of reason based on dependence\",\"tibetan\":\"དེ་ལ་ལྟོས་པའི་རིགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"apekṣāyukti\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"de la ltos pa’i rigs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"40949d3e-99d0-4594-a5d4-301c05db5056\",\"authority\":\"88fff44f-dabf-4206-a2ac-097a28c93254\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"principle of reason based on logical proof, principle of reason based on logical proof\",\"tibetan\":\"འཐད་པས་སྒྲུབ་པའི་རིགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"upa­pattisādhana­yukti\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’thad pas sgrub pa’i rigs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"71fa4121-69f9-4b8d-95c2-1b8127b13667\",\"authority\":\"95690a0a-43cb-40b4-bbf8-d637ebfb0aa5\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"principle of reason based on the nature of phenomena itself, principle of reason based on the nature of phenomena itself\",\"tibetan\":\"ཆོས་ཉིད་ཀྱི་རིགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dharmatāyukti\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"chos nyid kyi rigs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"465226ef-0ce7-4dc6-ab88-5bc18ee29c4b\",\"authority\":\"1c1202c5-a520-4e8b-9e84-b84ae43ed556\",\"definition\":\"$73\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"principle of reason, principles of reason\",\"tibetan\":\"རིགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"yukti\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rigs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"887e818e-8484-42c4-a942-a038f0577e6e\",\"authority\":\"45c05dfe-f89a-4664-ad72-960fa079206b\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"producing or bringing about a [new] existence\",\"tibetan\":\"ལུས་མངོན་པར་འགྲུབ་ཅིང་འབྱུང་བར་འགྱུར་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ātmabhāvam abhinirvartayanti\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lus mngon par ’grub cing ’byung bar ’gyur ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d9bbbe9e-7677-4d94-85cb-1af68799c360\",\"authority\":\"62e6b497-6fe8-4fce-898e-eb749e7b7fc5\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"purification\",\"tibetan\":\"རྣམ་པར་དག་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"viśuddhi\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rnam par dag pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"1934a994-1364-4f5e-8543-a01a9e2b989e\",\"authority\":\"ec34f1a6-e56d-4415-8509-5cafd7378c13\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eMahāvyutpatti 1113. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"purity of their merit\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡོན་ཡོངས་སུ་སྦྱོང་བ་ཆེན་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mahādakṣiṇāpariṣodhakaḥ\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"yon yongs su sbyong ba chen po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"db978d42-1d2b-4528-96ec-5d3723ce043c\",\"authority\":\"bf2e2c13-8e39-49ec-b907-82362bfcf784\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe polysemous word chos (usually a translation of dharma) is used here in the sense of “qualities,” as when someone or something is said to possess particularly efficacious, good, or beneficial qualities. It also can mean “virtue” in the nonreligious and nonmoral sense.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"quality\",\"tibetan\":\"ཆོས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dharma\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"chos\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2c0c941a-c063-48a8-ba69-41a78fa8b113\",\"authority\":\"934ff36f-2306-4019-bfb4-a9fe0ff6fa41\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe name of a bodhisattva \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-049-001-1624\\\"\u003estage\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Radiant\",\"tibetan\":\"འོད་འཕྲོ་བ་ཅན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"arciṣmatī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’od ’phro ba can\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f23c5032-1a66-4618-8e2a-104c5b84d8ea\",\"authority\":\"8e1e3d6b-46e3-4bdf-803b-17923bff3e62\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"reason\",\"tibetan\":\"རྟགས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"hetu\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rtags\"}},{\"uuid\":\"03f2ea5f-4956-49f2-a481-03a446bb4c0a\",\"authority\":\"fd818933-2312-40de-a844-833c9c8df93d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA general term applied to spiritual practitioners who live as ascetic mendicants. In Buddhist texts, the term usually refers to Buddhist monastics, but it can also designate a practitioner from other ascetic/monastic spiritual traditions. In this context \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eśramaṇa\u003c/em\u003e is often contrasted with the term \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003ebrāhmaṇa\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003ebram ze\u003c/em\u003e), which refers broadly to followers of the Vedic tradition. Any renunciate, not just a Buddhist, could be referred to as a śramaṇa if they were not within the Vedic fold. The epithet Great Śramaṇa is often applied to the Buddha.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"recluse\",\"tibetan\":\"དགེ་སྦྱོང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śrāmaṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dge sbyong\"}},{\"uuid\":\"079b3416-1bdc-4a62-a0e5-9f61b812e23d\",\"authority\":\"271bd849-aaa2-4cf0-8ef0-b82634cf1e9b\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"recollect what they have heard\",\"tibetan\":\"ཐོས་པའི་གཟུངས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śrutidhāraṇī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"thos pa’i gzungs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"32d38a05-df64-4e0b-89c0-d67fbf88da5e\",\"authority\":\"ecca035f-2474-4eec-9413-58bd0f18bcc5\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003edmigs (pa)\u003c/em\u003e translates a number of Sanskrit terms, including \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eālambana\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eupalabdhi\u003c/em\u003e, and \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eālambate\u003c/em\u003e. These terms commonly refer to the apprehending of a subject, an object, and the relationships that exist between them. The term may also be translated as “referentiality,” meaning a system based on the existence of referent objects, referent subjects, and the referential relationships that exist between them. As part of their doctrine of “threefold nonapprehending/nonreferentiality” (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003e’khor gsum mi dmigs pa\u003c/em\u003e), Mahāyāna Buddhists famously assert that all three categories of apprehending lack substantiality. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"referential object, ālambana\",\"tibetan\":\"དམིགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ālambana\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dmigs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"37607804-4d12-455a-aaba-4c5607dabf18\",\"authority\":\"b29381eb-19af-40c4-bec1-00cfa9f5b937\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"results produced by the maturation [of their karma], results produced by the maturation of their karma\",\"tibetan\":\"རྣམ་པར་སྨིན་པའི་འབྲས་བུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vipākaphala\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rnam par smin pa’i ’bras bu\"}},{\"uuid\":\"160c3de6-a6b2-44c9-befb-bbe0753c4b47\",\"authority\":\"36191161-3f52-4b2b-895b-935c71bc6692\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"room, underlying condition\",\"tibetan\":\"གནས་པ།, གནས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sthāna, sthāna\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gnas, gnas pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f96951ed-de18-4508-b236-6873fece0420\",\"authority\":\"36191161-3f52-4b2b-895b-935c71bc6692\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eSee Edgerton 1953, p. 579.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"room, underlying condition\",\"tibetan\":\"གནས་པ།, གནས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sthāna, sthāna\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gnas, gnas pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c81d5efb-6cb6-42b0-9a81-fd0651e41f73\",\"authority\":\"99e04700-b379-4487-96b7-bbf9e88970f5\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA sacred area located outside of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-049-001-1715\\\"\u003eVārāṇasī\u003c/span\u003e where many sages are said to have practiced in the past.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Ṛṣivadana\",\"tibetan\":\"དྲང་སྲོང་སྨྲ་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ṛṣivadana\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"drang srong smra ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"81afa7f5-c69e-45ee-9204-7b93cd2207b6\",\"authority\":\"4ae4c9aa-8fb4-4e8c-a310-b16650950946\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"sādhya, that which must be established, thing that must be established\",\"tibetan\":\"གྲུབ་པར་བྱ་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sādhya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"grub par bya ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"57b01614-c415-4ddf-865a-efa34ee98b71\",\"authority\":\"b715b65f-4d45-458a-a66d-dc44550300f0\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eTechnical term in Buddhist logic.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"sapakṣa\",\"tibetan\":\"\",\"sanskrit\":\"sapakṣa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ed0eb29f-3b54-4de3-8c74-33cc1c0e92f2\",\"authority\":\"e54e9b90-c990-455a-843d-3c8a628e9aa8\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eMahāvyutpatti 7470. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"scrutinizing\",\"tibetan\":\"ལྟ་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"prekṣate\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lta ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"fe2f8058-0ccd-4a55-ace7-1410a84bcb1a\",\"authority\":\"d647e044-0255-4f28-b89d-39e3479ad712\",\"definition\":\"$74\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"secondary defilement\",\"tibetan\":\"ཉེ་བའི་ཉོན་མོངས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"upakleśa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nye ba’i nyon mongs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"9661ded2-d387-44b2-87c7-3ebbaff2eb52\",\"authority\":\"98a2a6bf-fbf2-44ff-bddd-c53418bf76d5\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eThese can be listed as twelve or as six sense sources (sometimes also called sense fields, bases of cognition, or simply āyatanas).\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eIn the context of epistemology, it is one way of describing experience and the world in terms of twelve sense sources, which can be divided into inner and outer sense sources, namely: (1–2) eye and form, (3–4) ear and sound, (5–6) nose and odor, (7–8) tongue and taste, (9–10) body and touch, (11–12) mind and mental phenomena.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eIn the context of the twelve links of dependent origination, only six sense sources are mentioned, and they are the inner sense sources (identical to the six faculties) of eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"sense domain\",\"tibetan\":\"སྐྱེ་མཆེད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"āyatana\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"skye mched\"}},{\"uuid\":\"441f6371-895d-41b3-ade4-51346d8fab3c\",\"authority\":\"e85c6c76-76cf-489d-89db-b0b0161cd259\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"setting\",\"tibetan\":\"རབ་ཏུ་འཛིན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"pradhāraṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rab tu ’dzin pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c2db67b6-42db-4c9c-afbc-ad237b9e450d\",\"authority\":\"52322944-8a7f-47f2-aff9-48472209b78e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eThe set of seven precious materials or substances includes a range of precious metals and gems, but their exact list varies. The set often consists of gold, silver, beryl, crystal, red pearls, emeralds, and white coral, but may also contain lapis lazuli, ruby, sapphire, chrysoberyl, diamonds, etc. The term is frequently used in the sūtras to exemplify preciousness, wealth, and beauty, and can describe treasures, offering materials, or the features of architectural structures such as stūpas, palaces, thrones, etc. The set is also used to describe the beauty and prosperity of buddha realms and the realms of the gods.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eIn other contexts, the term \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003esaptaratna\u003c/em\u003e can also refer to the seven precious possessions of a cakravartin or to a set of seven precious moral qualities. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"seven precious substances\",\"tibetan\":\"རིན་པོ་ཆེ་སྣ་བདུན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"saptaratna\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rin po che sna bdun\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c7868db2-12bf-4d16-87e0-f05ff934fc17\",\"authority\":\"06dc9f27-995b-44db-aabe-11fd9e6134ba\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"sharing a common destiny\",\"tibetan\":\"བདེ་བ་གཅིག་པའི་དོན་གྱིས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ekayogakṣemārthena\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bde ba gcig pa’i don gyis\"}},{\"uuid\":\"68288101-966b-4cee-ae4b-f200a63046f6\",\"authority\":\"87756566-fb09-42f6-9f90-d463d4a11ddf\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eSee \u003ca href=\\\"end-notes.xhtml#UT22084-049-001-539\\\" data-pointer-type=\\\"id\\\"\u003en.191\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"shift in one’s basis of existence\",\"tibetan\":\"གནས་གྱུར་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"āśraya­parivṛtti\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gnas gyur pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"53a21c77-8b16-459a-b409-c3086bb96cbd\",\"authority\":\"dc281152-5c6f-4e2e-8f9f-45f1dfd52cad\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Single Vehicle\",\"tibetan\":\"ཐེག་པ་གཅིག་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ekayāna\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"theg pa gcig pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"762ae9fe-0856-486c-83ed-e29861bcf9e1\",\"authority\":\"9b02df99-ca46-4570-b32f-392f9c249f13\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe \u003cspan class=\\\"ignore\\\"\u003esix destinies\u003c/span\u003e correspond to the six realms of Buddhist cosmogony (i.e., gods, demigods, humans, animals, \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-049-001-1492\\\"\u003ehungry ghosts\u003c/span\u003e and \u003cspan\u003e\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-049-001-1719\\\"\u003ehell beings\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"six destinies\",\"tibetan\":\"འགྲོ་བ་དྲུག\",\"sanskrit\":\"sadgati\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’gro ba drug\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0a375424-2ca0-47b7-adb9-791280b8fe77\",\"authority\":\"3deb4e1e-ed43-4673-aee3-1737289c56a8\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"slow-witted\",\"tibetan\":\"བློ་གྲོས་ངན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kumati\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"blo gros ngan pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"fdcd6eda-4c35-412e-bc41-2fe6c612a934\",\"authority\":\"f42315f4-3cee-44ca-872f-8a076ac1f696\",\"definition\":\"$75\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"solitary realizer\",\"tibetan\":\"རང་སངས་རྒྱས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"pratyekabuddha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rang sangs rgyas\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d8dc547d-0e98-408b-bd49-c404b9e0782b\",\"authority\":\"ccf1d837-c138-401f-b29e-bc00f478ad23\",\"definition\":\"$76\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"sovereign power\",\"tibetan\":\"བྱིན་གྱི་རླབས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"adhiṣṭhita, adhiṣṭhāna\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"byin gyi rlabs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d2300647-ca09-4340-abb2-1af12d35d89f\",\"authority\":\"5ffe97c1-d347-41f1-9ba5-d874fe7ff0d8\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"space\",\"tibetan\":\"ནམ་མཁའ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ākāśa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nam mkha’\"}},{\"uuid\":\"4e64e8cc-e904-47f6-8554-e8273dd3587a\",\"authority\":\"c52879aa-5872-4ca4-935a-dfb2ee0305c7\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"stage\",\"tibetan\":\"ས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bhūmi\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d1a7b3f8-bb4e-4be0-a2b8-5aa4a439783f\",\"authority\":\"40887468-42d5-431d-8ed3-146432d4097f\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eMahāvyutpatti 897. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"stage of engagement through aspiration\",\"tibetan\":\"མོས་པ་སྤྱོད་པའི་ས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"adhimukticaryābhūmiḥ\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mos pa spyod pa’i sa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"bc76a676-6dad-4aed-ae06-3b5880c8357b\",\"authority\":\"34fdfa49-f501-49a6-bc05-843f1c927896\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"stainless\",\"tibetan\":\"སྦྱངས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"uttapta, viśuddha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sbyangs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"1641f442-0899-4ee1-8964-c7ce37aea883\",\"authority\":\"2e7857b6-c994-489d-9e24-3e1546dffd80\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe name of a bodhisattva \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-049-001-1624\\\"\u003estage\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Stainless\",\"tibetan\":\"དྲི་མ་མེད་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vimalā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dri ma med pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a4f0bca5-0c3c-4a9c-bcd5-32e2123a9e53\",\"authority\":\"9ae8a691-3333-4856-9d49-ea92ff3cd94b\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe name of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-049-001-1490\\\"\u003ehearer\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Subhūti\",\"tibetan\":\"རབ་འབྱོར།\",\"sanskrit\":\"subhūti\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rab ’byor\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7aac6c4a-42f6-48b9-b376-f43146706f21\",\"authority\":\"75ac4c58-10ba-4b16-99c3-7a8ee184d7da\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eSee “\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-049-001-1629\\\"\u003esubliminal cognition\u003c/span\u003e.”\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"subliminal\",\"tibetan\":\"ཀུན་གཞི།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ālaya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"kun gzhi\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c8f8f224-3598-42fb-8564-250f021425bd\",\"authority\":\"fdeda12e-e357-4dea-b28a-1d9ea7c5a5a9\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eSee Schmithausen’s groundbreaking work on the topic (1987 and 2014). Schmithausen considers the \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eālayavijñāna\u003c/em\u003e to be “a continuous \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-049-001-1628\\\"\u003esubliminal\u003c/span\u003e form of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-049-001-1542\\\"\u003emind\u003c/span\u003e” (Schmithausen 2014, p. 27).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"subliminal cognition, ālayavijñāna\",\"tibetan\":\"ཀུན་གཞི་རྣམ་པར་ཤེས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ālayavijñāna\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"kun gzhi rnam par shes pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"fe2fa218-ae9a-404e-bebd-9d7f114f0b9c\",\"authority\":\"fd1fa4cb-77c4-4265-9029-229cf3712906\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"subtle transgression\",\"tibetan\":\"ལྟུང་བ་ཕྲ་མོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sūkṣmāpatti\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ltung ba phra mo\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c85a7414-0934-4951-acb8-5a8da6980a66\",\"authority\":\"63994e60-3033-4fa4-bf71-e12d51f406f9\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eLit. “like the skin.”\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"superficial\",\"tibetan\":\"ལྤགས་ཤུན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lpags shun\"}},{\"uuid\":\"fd96b6d4-bd3f-4317-81d7-4267d8d2c1a8\",\"authority\":\"6564a075-184d-47f5-a065-80f538aef50b\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"superimpose, superimposition\",\"tibetan\":\"སྒྲོ་བཏགས།, སྒྲོ་འདོགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"samāropa, samāropa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sgro btags, sgro ’dogs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"af1bb170-3f26-444d-88e7-fbe86caadeaf\",\"authority\":\"6564a075-184d-47f5-a065-80f538aef50b\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"superimpose, superimposition\",\"tibetan\":\"སྒྲོ་བཏགས།, སྒྲོ་འདོགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"samāropa, samāropa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":